Imagine a very long web page with many sections (for example, a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific section (for example, page.html#section7), can the Web server first transmit that section and then transmit the other sections?
Stream order:
1. The beginning of the HTML document up to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for section 7
3. The HTML code for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser needs to ensure that sections 1 through 6 are inserted above section 7 on the web page.
Is this reasonable? Would it be useful?
The goal I want to achieve is to have the linked section (#section7) rendered as soon as possible, without having to reimplement it using JavaScript or similar technologies. I want a very long HTML document, but the linked section should still be rendered quickly. This should be achievable with just HTML.
The content can be streamed in this way, and the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7> section 7… </div>
<contents for=sec1> section 1… </contents>
<contents for=sec2> section 2… </contents>
etc.
Although the order of streaming is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 Actually, it is possible to reorder the document content without using JS. However, if you want the server to do something, you cannot use the hash part of the URL, but instead use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to see first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use templates with slots
@user23 That's right. The issue is that the visual order (as seen by the user) does not match the DOM order. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, while the browser arranges the content in order within the DOM, that might be very useful.
However, the slot method seems promising. I'll try it out.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 Exactly, that's what I'm thinking. The only reason for sending section 7 first is to let the user see it as soon as possible. If this can be achieved without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, allowing the browser to ensure the final DOM order and visual order are consistent.
In other words, send section 7 first, but the final result (DOM and visual appearance) should be exactly the same as if all sections were sent in order.
@user22 @user33 You can check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
